# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the years 1845 to 1868 throughout the world.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At its December 1868 annual meeting, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) permitted professional clubs.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twelve existing members did "go pro" and constitute the professional field for 1869.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1868 season records for 98 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 15 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors" (not marked), all of the 1869 "pros" (*), all 14 member clubs with at least twelve wins on record, and a few others.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the seven listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At least four Association clubs not listed here would someday try professionalism: Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio (1870); Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana (1871); Middletown of Mansfield, Connecticut (1872); Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey (1873).
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Meanwhile, only two brand new professional baseball clubs would be established in the next three years, the Chicago White Stockings for 1870 and the Boston Red Stockings for 1871.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Their commercial origins may be related to their survival alone by 1877, and on to 2010, while all of their rivals with older and amateur roots fell away.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1867 season records for 89 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 17 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 13 member clubs with at least fourteen wins on record, and a few others.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the nine listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks ten clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Excelsior of Chicago and Buckeye of Cincinnati are listed because they were probably the strongest teams in the west after the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1866 season records for 58 of 93 association members, said to be complete for games between two member clubs.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 20 of that season's teams "major" including three old New York rivals of the Knickerbockers.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 14 members with at least eight wins on record, and a few others.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the fifteen listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks eight clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869, three seasons later.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the preceding 1865 season Marshall Wright lists 30 members with supposedly complete records for most of them.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twenty-two of the thirty were in Greater New York.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 19 teams "major" in the first season that he covers: sixteen of the members and three others (Lowell, Harvard, and Camden).
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] No one traveled much and membership was still depressed by the Civil War.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] There had been 59 delegates at the March 1860 annual meeting, and 55 at the next annual meeting that December (on a new baseball calendar), who thereby intended to play during the 1861 season that the war curtailed.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Nine of 59 and eleven of 55 were from outside Greater New York.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players, the Athletic Baseball Club of Philadelphia was one of the first clubs to join.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Athletics had been around since 1860 as an amateur club.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] Led by their captain and pitcher, Dick McBride, the team went 21–7 and won the first NA title during the 1871 season.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] Philadelphia's third baseman, Levi Meyerle, led the league with a .492 batting average.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1872 Boston Red Stockings season** was the second season of the franchise.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] They won the National Association championship.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 39–8 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 48 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 38 wins.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .430 batting average.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1872-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1872 throughout the world.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1872-philadelphia-athletics-season] In its second year in the National Association, the **1872 Athletic Baseball Club of Philadelphia** finished in fourth place with a record of 30–14.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1873 Boston Red Stockings season** was the third season of the franchise.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their second consecutive National Association championship.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 43–16 to win the pennant by 4 games.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 54 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 41 wins.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .431 batting average, and catcher Deacon White topped the circuit with 77 runs batted in.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] The **National Association of Professional Base Ball Players** (**NAPBBP**), often known simply as the **National Association** (**NA**), was the first fully-professional sports league in baseball.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] The NA was founded in 1871 and continued through the 1875 season.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] It incorporated several professional clubs from the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) of 1857–1870, sometimes called "the amateur Association".
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Following nearly a century of cooperation, the two leagues eventually merged into one organization in 2000 as Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] In 1869, the previously amateur National Association of Base Ball Players, in response to concerns that some teams were paying players, established a professional category.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] The Cincinnati Red Stockings were the first team to declare their desire to become fully professional.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] By 1871, several clubs, wanting to separate fully from the amateur association, broke away to found the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] (The remaining amateur clubs founded the National Association of Amateur Base Ball Players, which only lasted two years).
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] In 1876, wanting an even stronger central organization, six clubs from the NA and two independents established the National League: Boston Red Stockings, Hartford, Mutual, Athletic, Chicago, and the St.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Louis Brown Stockings from the NA plus independent clubs Louisville and Cincinnati.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Whether to cover the NA as a major league is a recurring matter of difference in historical work on American baseball among historians, encyclopedists, database builders, and others.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Major League Baseball and the National Baseball Hall of Fame do not recognize it as a major league, but the NA comprised most of the professional clubs and the highest caliber of play then in existence.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Its players, managers, and umpires are included among the "major leaguers" who define the scope within baseball references such as Retrosheet.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] In 1969, Major League Baseball's newly formed Special Baseball Records Committee decided that the National Association should be excluded from major league status, citing the association's "erratic schedule and procedures" as well as a history of gambling and "poor newspaper coverage".
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Thus, when the landmark 1969 *Macmillan Baseball Encyclopedia* was published, National Association records were not included in totals for such early stars as Cap Anson.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Arguments against including the NA as a major league generally revolve around the league's quality of play, significant differences in the sport's rules during the era, and the instability of the league (as many teams lasted only one season or part of a season), and the poor state of the NA records.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] The Special Baseball Records Committee's decision has faced continuing criticism.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] In 1982, *Sports Illustrated* writer Marc Onigman argued that the NA should be included in the major leagues, despite its acknowledged flaws, pointing out the same flaws existed in other leagues as well, and called the Committee's decision "a modern-day value judgment that doesn't hold up".
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] The committee's decision has been criticized for favoring the owner-run National League over the player-dominated National Association.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Professional baseball clubs in the 19th century were often known by what is now regarded as a "nickname", although it was actually the club's name.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] This was a practice carried over from the amateur days.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] The singular form of a "nickname" was often the team name itself, with its base city "understood" and was so listed in the standings; for example the Atlantic Base Ball Club, which was located in Brooklyn.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Rather than "Brooklyn Atlantics", the team was simply called "Atlantic", or "Atlantic of Brooklyn" if deemed necessary by the writer.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Another common practice was to refer to the team in the plural, hence the "Bostons" the "Chicagos" or the "Mutuals".
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] This practice of using the singular form of the "nickname" as the team name faded with time, although as recently as the early 1900s the team generally known as "Philadelphia Athletics" was shown in the American League standings as the traditional way of "Athletic".
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] That team sported a blackletter-style "A" on its jerseys, as had previous teams based in Philadelphia and using the same name.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Later, the *Encyclopedia of Baseball* attempted to retrofit the names into a modern context.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] In the following list, the bold names are the names most often used by contemporary newspapers in league standings, and the linked names after them are those typically ascribed to the teams now, using the *Encyclopedia of Baseball* standard.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Before 1883, team order in baseball standings was determined by the number of games a team won, not by winning percentage.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] For each of the five NA seasons, the league champion had both the most games won and the best winning percentage.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] The placement of other clubs may vary—for example, the 1872 Philadelphia Athletics finished in fourth place (based on their win total), while recording the second-best winning percentage.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] The NA did not have a postseason; champions were determined by final standings at the end of the season.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] † Individual statistics from tie games count towards players' career totals, but tie games are excluded when computing winning percentage and games behind.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] George Wright was the first NA inductee (1937) and Deacon White is the most recent (2013).
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Four of the eight had significant playing careers in the National League or other major leagues after their time in the NA: Anson, Galvin, O'Rourke, and White, each of whom was inducted into the Hall of Fame as a player.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] The other four—Cummings, Spalding, and brothers George and Harry Wright—were each inducted into the Hall as an "executive", a Hall of Fame category that includes pioneers of the game.
[src:national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players/national-association-of-professional-base-ball-players] Cummings is notable for being the pitcher credited with inventing the curveball.
